<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Event Points
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        A high-level introduction to Event Points, mission logic, event point categories, and the Add New EventPoint window.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Event Points Are
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Event Points are the foundation of mission logic. A mission is built by placing event points
        on the map and configuring what each one does. Some event points create things, some trigger
        actions, some display messages, some control cameras, some affect NPC behaviour, and some
        end the mission.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Event points can also be linked through IDs, colour groups, letter groups, counters, timers,
        and references to other event points. This is how objectives, sub-objectives, mission
        sequences, failure conditions, and bonus conditions are created.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_eventpoints_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Adding an Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To add an event point, click the <Bold>Add</Bold> button in the Event Points panel. This
        opens the <Bold>Add New EventPoint</Bold> window.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_eventpoints_add_button.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        The Add New EventPoint window presents a list of possible event point types. The type you
        choose depends on what you want the mission to do.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_eventpoints_add_window.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    When building a mission from scratch, start with the basics: create the player,
                    place any required NPCs or items, then add objectives, messages, counters, and win/lose conditions.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Event Point Categories
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        There are many event point types. A useful way to understand them is to group them into
        broad categories:
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Player</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Adds or defines the player character for the mission, such as Darci or Roper.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">NPCs</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Adds extra police, enemies, citizens, or other people to the mission.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Items</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Adds pickups, cones, barrels, powerups, mission objects, and related interactable items.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Traps</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Adds hazards such as steam jets, traps, bombs, or other dangerous mission objects.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Camera</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates camera sequences, camera targets, waypoints, and cutscene-related movement.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Map Exits</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Older or mostly unused event points for mission/map exits.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Text Messages</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Handles conversations, shouts, radio messages, mission text, and on-screen messages.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Miscellaneous</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Contains counters, timers, teleports, dynamic lights, prim actions, group life/death/reset, autosave, and other mission logic.</Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        High-Level Event Point Reference
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The following list is a high-level overview of common Event Point types. Later sections can
        go into each type in more detail.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Create Player</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Spawns or defines the player character/start point for the mission.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Create Enemies / Create Enemy</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates one or more NPC or enemy characters with chosen type, behaviour, weapon, flags, and related settings.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Create Vehicle</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Spawns a vehicle at the event point position.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Create Item</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates a pickup or item at the event point location.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Create Creature</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Spawns a creature or non-human actor using creature-specific type data.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Create Camera / Camera Waypoint</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates a scripted camera node or additional waypoint for camera movement.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Create Target / Target Waypoint</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates a camera target or target path node for scripted camera aiming.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Simple</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">A basic marker or trigger event point with no special type-specific data.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Move Thing</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Moves a referenced event point or object to this event point’s position.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Adjust Enemy / Enemy Flags</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Changes an existing enemy or person’s behaviour, flags, AI state, or related settings.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Visual Effect / Spot Effect / Create Mist</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates visual, spot, or atmospheric effects at the event point position.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Dynamic Light</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates or controls an animated dynamic light, including type, speed, step pattern, and colour values.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Sound Effect</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Plays a sound or music entry by index from the global sound list.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Message / Shout / Conversation</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Displays messages, shouts, or conversation text/audio-style mission dialogue.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">CutScene</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Triggers an embedded cutscene blob stored in the mission extra-data stream.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Nav Beacon</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates an objective/navigation beacon, optionally attached to a person or event point.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">End Game Win / End Game Lose</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Ends the mission as either success or failure.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Bonus Points</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Awards bonus score and usually displays associated bonus text.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Create Barrel / Create Bomb / Create Trap</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates barrels, bombs, explosives, traps, or hazard objects.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Activate Prim / Burn Prim / Make Searchable</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Changes nearby or referenced prim/object state, including activation, burning, or making an object searchable.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Create Treasure</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates or defines a treasure or hidden item reward.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">WareFX / Warehouse FX</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Applies an area audio-visual preset such as silence, Police HQ, restaurant, office, or club music.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Sign</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Displays a road or street sign graphic on screen.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">No Floor / Shake Camera / Autosave / Interesting</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Presence-style event points that mark a location or trigger a specific built-in behaviour.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Teleport / Teleport Target</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates a teleport entrance and destination pairing, likely grouped by common mission grouping data.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Link Platform</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Links or configures a moving platform, including speed and platform flags.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Lock Vehicle / Stall Car</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Locks, unlocks, stalls, or disables a vehicle.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Transfer Player / Kill Waypoint</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Transfers the player to another target or stops another event point from processing.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Group Life / Group Death / Group Reset</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Controls all waypoints in the same colour/group by making them alive, dead, or reset.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Increment / Reset Counter / Extend Timer / Count Up Timer</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Controls mission counters and timers used for objectives, logic gates, and timed conditions.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Make Person Pee / Cone Penalties / GothereDothis</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Specialised mission behaviour event points. Some of these still require source confirmation before all editable fields are fully documented.</Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- COMMON EVENT POINT PROPERTIES -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Most Event Point types share a group of common properties. These are used for identification,
        grouping, filtering, and linking.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Index Number</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The event point index. This is assigned automatically by the editor.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Type</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The Event Point type. This is set automatically based on the type selected in the
        <Bold>Add New EventPoint</Bold> window.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Letter Group</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A grouping value from
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">A</Run>
        to
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">Z</Run>.
        Letter groups help organise event points and may be important for some linking behaviours.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Colour</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A colour group used for organisation, filtering, and some mission logic. Event points can be
        filtered by colour in the Filters panel.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,8,0,0">
        Letter and colour groups are useful for keeping related Event Points together. They can also
        matter to mission logic, especially where Event Points are linked by group, filtered by group,
        or interpreted as part of a chain such as patrol waypoints, objectives, counters, targets, or
        scripted mission actions.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- EVENT POINT POSITION -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Position values define where an Event Point exists in the world. These values are stored
        in <Bold>world coordinates</Bold>, not screen pixels.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        You can type the position manually if you know the exact coordinates, but the easier method
        is to use the map selection tool.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Selecting the Position on the Map
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Click <Bold>Select Position on Map</Bold>, then click the desired location in the viewport.
        The Event Point position updates to the clicked location.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Use the map layers to choose a sensible location. Textures, buildings, objects, walkable
        areas, lights, and other visible Event Points can all help you avoid placing mission logic
        inside geometry, behind walls, outside the playable area, or somewhere that is hard to debug.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- EVENT POINT DIRECTION -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Direction and Rotation
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Event Points also store a <Bold>Direction</Bold> value. This controls which way the Event Point
        is facing. The value is stored as a byte from
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">0</Run>
        to
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">255</Run>,
        which the editor displays as degrees.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        When direction arrows are visible, the selected Event Point shows an orange rotation handle
        at the end of its direction arrow. Drag that handle to rotate the Event Point on the map.
        The numeric Direction field updates as the handle moves.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Rotation is useful for any Event Point whose behaviour depends on facing, such as characters,
        creatures, cameras, traps, target points, directional triggers, and scripted interactions.
        Type-specific help pages may describe how direction affects that particular Event Point, but
        the rotate-and-face interaction is common to Event Points in general.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Event Point Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Load or create a mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Load the map and light file for visual reference.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select the event point type that matches the mission action you need.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place or configure the event point as required.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use filters to keep the event point list manageable.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Link event points using IDs, colour groups, letter groups, counters, timers, or type-specific references.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

